<section class="thesis-pillars not-content">
  <article>
    <p class="thesis-pillars__label">Multitier</p>
    <h3>Where computation lives</h3>
    <p>
      Place code and data explicitly across peers such as clients, servers, dashboards, edge nodes,
      and devices.
    </p>
  </article>
  <article>
    <p class="thesis-pillars__label">Choreography</p>
    <h3>Deadlock-free peer interaction</h3>
    <p>
      Describe cross-host communication in program order instead of scattering message handlers,
      callbacks, and protocol state throughout the codebase.
    </p>
  </article>
  <article>
    <p class="thesis-pillars__label">Aggregate</p>
    <h3>Collective-adaptive behaviors</h3>
    <p>
      Model ensembles of devices as collective computations over local observations, time, and
      neighboring peers.
    </p>
  </article>
  <article class="thesis-pillars__foundation">
    <p class="thesis-pillars__label">Shared foundation</p>
    <h3>Capabilities + placement types</h3>
    <p>
      The paper's core idea is that paradigm-specific operations can be guarded by capabilities,
      while placement types regulate where values live and how they move between peers.
    </p>
  </article>
</section>

